“Yes, Captain. They should be on their way by now, they were still in the mess hall to pick up their food.” At exactly 0500, the Exodus Company gathered at the armory. Shaw climbed onto a box and began speaking.
“We will be relocated to the forward deployment base I-131, fifty miles outside of Ianlos. Our task is to support the ongoing siege and later attack on Ianlos to drive out the rebels. We will establish a base at the foot of the mountains,” explained Shaw. “Break into your squads and get on board.”
The company broke up into their respective squads, and the soldiers were distributed among the tanks by the petty officers. Cohren climbed into one of the tanks further back in the convoy, where he met Nemic, Craith, and two new recruits. Cohren remembered the arrival of the two a few days ago but knew little about them. He sat on the side and let his legs dangle as he adjusted his backpack and the radio connected to his headphones and throat microphone.
“Hey Cohren, is Snowball still with Harris?” Nemic asked after they had settled in.
“Do you mean the chicken he stole?” Cohren recalled the morning when they let the animal go on a farmer's field. “Yes, I think so.”
Cohren looked over to one of the other tanks and spotted Harris with his squad. From the corner of his eye, he could see the movement of a small bird constantly turning its head to search the surroundings.
“Yes, he’s still with them,” Cohren replied as the hatch of the tank opened and the commander came into view.
“All tanks move out,” the commander spoke slowly and calmly into his headset. The engines of the tank column and Strykers roared as they started moving. Cohren’s ride, the Kronos tank, shook when the brakes were released and they fell into formation. The tanks moved in a V-shaped formation across the Itania plain. Despite the winter storms, the swamp areas were frozen and the forests snowed over, but mud was everywhere.
About an hour later, one of the recruits, whom Cohren knew was named Orson, began to speak. “Lieutenant, you’ve been here since the start of the war, right?”
“Yes, Operation Firestorm,” Cohren answered. “We thought it would be done in a few weeks, but we underestimated them.”
“Underestimating them is seriously understated,” Nemic interjected into the conversation. “We were not prepared for their arsenal and the number of soldiers. They destroyed the UFS Revenant in the first two weeks and only last month took down the Erebus. We should even see them on our route.”
“I stand firmly with the Federation,” Orson said defiantly. “I will not be intimidated by these terrorists.”
“You say that now. But I have seen that most eighteen-year-old recruits like you tend to seek cover very quickly as soon as they hear a shot,” Craith explained.
“We shall see,” Cohren said laughingly. The conversation ended with Orson.
“Exodus XO, Exodus CO,” crackled Cohren’s radio. “We are receiving thermal signatures, approximately 300 meters away, 20 degrees to the right.”
Cohren climbed up onto the tank and put on his special glasses. As he switched them to "thermal image," he could see the signatures in the distance.
“Yes, I see them,” Cohren replied over his throat microphone.
“Are they hostile?” asked the other recruit, Natayla.
“I can’t tell,” Cohren responded. He reached for his microphone and said: “Exodus Company, fire only when under attack. Let’s lure them out.”
As they approached, the point-like thermal signatures took shape. When they came even closer, one of them ran quickly away to get something. She immediately returned to the small hill where the others were located. The figures lay down on the ground, taking position for firing.
"We have enemy contact," Shaw called over the radio as orange tracer bullets were fired from the hilltop. While the tanks came under fire, the assault troops jumped down and took cover. A rocket flew past and hit the ground behind the formation, exploding and scattering debris onto one of the tanks. Another landed beside a Stryker, an APS-Cerberus, and exploded. The crew quickly climbed out and took cover as the ammunition sprayed into the air.
"Iron 1-2 and 1-3, 25 degrees right, 300 meters. Fire," shouted the tank platoon commander over the radio. Iron 1-2 and 1-3 opened fire, grenades flying towards the hill and exploding, sending dirt and stone into the air.
"Send the Sentis in," Knoxx called, observing the hill through binoculars. The back door of a Cerberus opened, and an unarmed soldier wearing a special headset emerged. He spoke commands into a square microphone, and two Sentis, officially called Sentinels, stormed out. With their thin metal arms and legs swinging forward, they began running. They carried their weapons on their backs.
"Kill or capture?" Craith asked, watching them.
"Looks like capture," Cohren guessed, as the two Sentinels disappeared into the ash and smoke. Screams and gunfire echoed from the hill, but soon quieted. A short while later, the two Sentinels returned, dragging someone behind them whose boots left marks in the ground. After retreating to the protection of the platoon, they dropped the figure onto the ground. It groaned in pain as it landed hard in the mud and snow.
Shaw went to the figure that was just trying to stand up. Then he turned to one of the sentinels. "How many?"
"Three dead, sir," answered the sentinel. "The rest fled on foot."
Shaw nodded and turned to Cohren and Craith, who stood nearby. "Get this guy out of my sight!"
